00:03:30.320 --> 00:03:36.840
Okay, so now let's have a look at a rather&nbsp;
specific case of 2x2 matrices with determinant&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:36.840 --> 00:03:44.400
one where we're looking at everything from the&nbsp;
point of view of mod 2 arithmetic. In mod 2&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:44.400 --> 00:03:49.200
arithmetic, it's a very simple kind of modular&nbsp;
arithmetic—there are really only two values,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:49.200 --> 00:03:58.080
zero and one, because two is declared to be like&nbsp;
zero. So the group that we're defining here is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:58.080 --> 00:04:06.480
a set of matrices a, b, c, d where the entries&nbsp;
a, b, c, d are all from the set zero and one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:06.480 --> 00:04:16.200
so each entry is either 0 or 1 and the overall&nbsp;
determinant a d minus b c is congruent to 1 mod 2,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:16.200 --> 00:04:23.000
so it could be one or it could also be minus&nbsp;
one because mod 2 minus one is the same as&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:32.320
one and the multiplication, we state that this&nbsp;
is the multiplication of matrices mod 2. That&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:32.320 --> 00:04:39.760
means after you do the multiplication you simplify&nbsp;
everything mod 2. Okay, so this is definitely an&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:39.760 --> 00:04:52.600
A3 Prime type of definition in that we are using&nbsp;
descriptive language to specify the set and also,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:52.600 --> 00:04:58.360
well, we're basically sort of talking about what&nbsp;
the multiplication is instead of laying it out&nbsp;&nbsp;

