00:13:31.440 --> 00:13:36.920
Okay, so this is a very interesting group and&nbsp;
it's actually a group that's studied very much&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:36.920 --> 00:13:43.960
in number theory and in geometry as well. So it's&nbsp;
a very important group mathematically, SL2 over&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:43.960 --> 00:13:52.280
the integers, but it's an infinite group via this&nbsp;
A3 Prime definition. So in modern mathematics, we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:52.280 --> 00:13:59.080
do not, we do not have any problems with making a&nbsp;
definition like this. So this would be absolutely&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:59.080 --> 00:14:05.480
routine kind of definition that you would find in&nbsp;
mathematical papers throughout the subject. But we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:05.480 --> 00:14:12.040
are going to look more skeptically at this because&nbsp;
we recognize that this definition here, this A3&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:12.040 --> 00:14:19.520
Prime kind of definition, really finesses some&nbsp;
key points, namely it doesn't tell us explicitly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:19.520 --> 00:14:24.440
what all the objects are and it doesn't tell&nbsp;
us explicitly what the multiplication actually&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:24.440 --> 00:14:32.000
is. It's up for us to generate elements, and we're&nbsp;
only going to be able to do that obviously sort of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:32.000 --> 00:14:39.400
up to a point because there's an unbounded number&nbsp;
of these determinant one 2x2 integral matrices,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:39.400 --> 00:14:45.920
and it's up to us to sort of work out what the&nbsp;
multiplication table is from this sort of basic&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:45.920 --> 00:14:55.120
direction here. So this kind of definition is&nbsp;
definitely not in the spirit of A1 and A2, and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:55.120 --> 00:15:01.280
in fact from the spirit of A1 and A2, if you had&nbsp;
that as your orientation, you would not be able to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:01.280 --> 00:15:06.960
take this and to transform it into something that&nbsp;
was meaningful to you, right? If you're a computer&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:06.960 --> 00:15:16.360
that has been trained to understand that a group&nbsp;
is a an array with you know index by 1 to K, 1 to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:16.360 --> 00:15:22.960
K, it's a K by K array with certain properties,&nbsp;
you're not going to be able to express this in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:22.960 --> 00:15:29.400
that language. This is going to be outside your&nbsp;
understanding. Similarly with the A2 definition,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:29.400 --> 00:15:35.240
even if you're allowed to not use the numbers 1&nbsp;
through K, but rather some arbitrary kind of set,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:35.240 --> 00:15:41.960
you're still not able to list all of the elements.&nbsp;
And when we start thinking about things, okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:41.960 --> 00:15:47.400
when we start thinking especially with the point&nbsp;
of view of bigger numbers, we start to appreciate&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:47.400 --> 00:15:55.720
that a lot of these matrices inevitably are going&nbsp;
to end up involving very big numbers, and then we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:55.720 --> 00:16:00.480
run into the same kinds of problems that we do&nbsp;
when we're considering the set of numbers from&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:00.480 --> 00:16:06.560
one to Z. We talked before about this, right? What&nbsp;
does it mean to talk about the set of numbers from&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:06.560 --> 00:16:12.200
one to Z because we know that most of those&nbsp;
numbers are too big to fit into the known&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:12.200 --> 00:16:21.200
universe. They are completely invisible to us.&nbsp;
Well, very similarly, that's going to happen with&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:21.200 --> 00:16:27.440
the entries of this group as well. Most of these&nbsp;
matrices that we're going to end up considering&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:27.440 --> 00:16:34.000
are going to have entries which are so big that&nbsp;
they don't fit into the universe. So exactly the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:34.000 --> 00:16:38.880
same kind of problems are going to occur here&nbsp;
that it's no longer clear that we really have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:38.880 --> 00:16:45.760
control over all such matrices. In reality,&nbsp;
we only have control up to a certain point,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:45.760 --> 00:16:50.360
up to the point that we're able to do arithmetic,&nbsp;
but here we're positing that we are going to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:50.360 --> 00:16:57.800
consider this whole thing even beyond the limits&nbsp;
of our arithmetic. Okay, so from a computational&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:57.800 --> 00:17:06.320
point of view, this is fraught with difficulties.&nbsp;
But modern mathematics doesn't recognize that,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:06.320 --> 00:17:12.920
doesn't see that, because it's quite happy&nbsp;
to allow such sort of sloppy definitions,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:12.920 --> 00:17:19.480
because for one thing it makes it easier to make&nbsp;
this transition from finite to infinite things,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:19.480 --> 00:17:24.480
because if you're not going to be concrete about&nbsp;
specifying stuff, then it doesn't really matter if&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:24.480 --> 00:17:30.960
you become a little bit more sloppy by introducing&nbsp;
an infinite number of things into the story,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:30.960 --> 00:17:37.000
infinite number in quotes. So let me phrase what&nbsp;
we've been discussing in the following lesson,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:37.000 --> 00:17:44.040
that if we use the sloppy A3 Prime definition&nbsp;
or description of a group, and I'm inclined to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:44.040 --> 00:17:49.440
think of it more as a description rather than&nbsp;
a definition, then we can substitute infinite&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:49.440 --> 00:17:54.720
set for finite set with impunity because part of&nbsp;
the whole story is that we are not being careful&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:54.720 --> 00:18:03.280
about what the word set means in the first place.&nbsp;
But on the other hand, if we adopt a more careful&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:03.280 --> 00:18:10.720
computational approach along the lines of the A1&nbsp;
or A2 definitions which are geared more towards&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:10.720 --> 00:18:17.760
what a computer can understand, then we must&nbsp;
do more work if we want to go from the finite&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:17.760 --> 00:18:24.160
group definition to an infinite group definition.&nbsp;
It's not enough just to replace the word group&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:24.160 --> 00:18:30.960
or finite group with the word infinite group. We&nbsp;
must actually understand things from a different&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:30.960 --> 00:18:37.280
point of view. So we're going to need separate&nbsp;
definitions of group and infinite group. These are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:37.280 --> 00:18:43.840
not going to be things which are found in the same&nbsp;
basket. How to do this is a very good question and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:43.840 --> 00:18:49.920
we are going to talk about that. But at this&nbsp;
point, I just want to flag that there is a big&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:49.920 --> 00:18:56.400
jump if you're going to do things properly between&nbsp;
understanding finite concrete explicit objects and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:56.400 --> 00:19:02.200
infinite versions of them. All right, currently we&nbsp;
only have quotes around all the infinite versions,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:02.200 --> 00:19:08.360
and to make theories where there's no quotes and&nbsp;
things are actually precise, a lot more work is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:08.360 --> 00:19:17.560
required. In our next video, I want to talk about&nbsp;
our third issue that abstract algebra really needs&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:17.560 --> 00:19:22.160
to wrestle with, and that's the fundamental&nbsp;
theorem of algebra. All right, so we're going&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:22.160 --> 00:19:33.800
to have to say some uncomfortable truths about the&nbsp;
